Activity TASK - Before starting work inspect the area to ensure that the subgrade is to the specified standard, free from soft spots, to the correct falls and all services completed, to allow work of the required standard.
Acceptance Criteria - Before you Dig consulted and deployed on site – Inspected by Project Engineer/Project manager
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Before you Dig report and marking on site
INTERNAL VERIFICATION AUTHORITY OR RESPONSIBILITY - Internal Project Engineer / Project Manager
Activity TASK - Ensure the formation to bedding sub-base level for kerb and/or channel is well compacted, smooth, uniform and to the required level.

Acceptance Criteria - Unless otherwise shown on drawings, bed concrete on not less than 75m thick compacted sub basecourse layer forming the adjacent pavement or GAP40. – On site inspection by Project manager.
FREQUENCY - Every new section of Kerb and channel.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Photo Evidence with Comments to Client Engineer.

Activity TASK - The finished kerb and channel shall be made using 20 MPa Concrete in accordance with the Territorial Authority Standard Detail for slip formed kerb and channel, or if the Territorial Authority does not have its own standard, in accordance with that shown in NZS4404. (Figure 3.7 Kerbs and Dished Channels)
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Photo Evidence with Comments to Client Engineer / Project Manager
• Confirm the use of forms for extruded or in situ kerbs which vary in section from those detailed.

• Unless the contractor has obtained the prior written approval of the territorial authority and is able to satisfy the engineer that the finished product will be satisfactory in both quality and alignment, alternative cross sections will not be permitted.
Acceptance Criteria - On-site inspection and acceptance by Engineer.
FREQUENCY - Prior to work being undertaken
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Signoff by Engineer.

Activity TASK - Lay edging, kerbs and gutter channels, true and straight to grade, alignment and level. Curves to sweep evenly around bends without kinks, flats or angles. Form bends in precast kerbing with purpose-made corner blocks.
Acceptance Criteria - Onsite inspection by Project Engineer/Project Manager.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Photo Evidence to Project Manager
INTERNAL VERIFICATION AUTHORITY OR RESPONSIBILITY - Internal Project Engineer / Project Manager

• Form construction joints in boxed channels at 4.0m maximum centres either by pouring alternate sections and painting exposed ends with bitumen emulsion paint, or by providing bituminous fabric or fibreboard stops in the formwork.
• Form construction joints in-situ or extruded kerbs and channels by cutting to 30mm deep max at 3.0 metre centres maximum and at each side of the vehicle crossing. Form around catchpits and sumps.
Acceptance Criteria - On-site inspection and acceptance by Engineer.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Signoff by Engineer.
• Excavate, box for in situ concrete dish channel, place 3 x 10mm diameter reinforcing and cast as detailed using 20 MPa concrete, with construction joints every 4.0 metres maximum.

• Channel to be 600mm wide and 200mm deep with 30mm dish as detailed. Form around catch pits and sumps. Exposed surfaces to show an even surface texture, with no honeycombing, hollows, fins, steps or air bubbles.
• Allow concrete to cure before making good the adjoining basecourse.
Acceptance Criteria - On-site inspection and acceptance by Engineer.
FREQUENCY - Inspection upon completion of drainage and prior to backfilling.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Signoff by Engineer.
• Excavate, box for in situ concrete flush kerb and gutter channels and cast as detailed using 20 MPa concrete, with construction joints every 4.0 metres maximum.
• Exposed surfaces to show an even smooth surface texture, with no honeycombing, hollows, fins, steps or air bubbles.
• Allow concrete to cure before making good the adjoining basecourse.
Acceptance Criteria - On-site inspection and acceptance by Engineer.
FREQUENCY - Inspection upon completion of drainage and prior to backfilling.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Signoff by Engineer.

Activity TASK - Boxing shall be true and straight and shall conform to the lines and levels shown on the drawings. It shall not be set up until after the sub basecourse has been laid and shall not be stripped until the concrete is at least 36 hours old.
Acceptance Criteria - Onsite inspection by Project Engineer/Project Manager
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Photo Evidence to Project Manager
INTERNAL VERIFICATION AUTHORITY OR RESPONSIBILITY - Internal Project Engineer / Project Manager
• Carry out backfilling and compacting behind the kerb in conjunction with base course construction to ensure even support to the kerb.
• The fill operation shall be carefully controlled to ensure that the kerb is not displaced or damaged and the subbase and basecourse are not contaminated by the backfill material.
• Do not carry out basecourse construction immediately adjacent to the kerb until at least three days after the kerb poured.
Acceptance Criteria - Onsite inspection by Project Engineer/Project Manager.
CERTIFYING DOCUMENTATION, RECORD OR CHECKSHEET - Photo Evidence to Project Manager
INTERNAL VERIFICATION AUTHORITY OR RESPONSIBILITY - Internal Project Engineer / Project Manager
• Contact DBYD and complete excavation permit
• Extent of works set out with survey pegs

• Carry out control testing on each batch of geotextile delivered to site to ensure conformity for the properties specified in Tables R63/E.1 and R63/E.2. Testing must include the mean weight of the geotextile, determined as per AS 3706.1 and AS 2001.2.13
• Frequency of sampling and testing as per Table R63.1
• WITNESS POINT: Sampling of geotextile on site. Submit to the Client: Location, date and time of sampling and person sampling

• Provide a Certificate of Compliance that the geotextile complies with all the requirements of this specification for its specified usage, together with test results reported on NATA-endorsed test documents. The certificate must not be more than 12 months old.
• The Client may accept test certificates for tests carried out for other projects from the same batch samples taken at site for the Client.
• HOLD POINT: Supply of geotextile. Submit to the Client: Certificate of Compliance from the supplier, and nomination of where each strength and filtration class will be used
• Geotextiles must be stored under protective cover or wrapped with a waterproof, opaque UV protective sheeting to avoid any damage prior to installation.
• Do not store materials directly on the ground or where they may be affected by heat, dirt or damage.
• Place the geotextiles in accordance with the Specifications and as shown on the Drawings.
• Unless specified otherwise, select geotextiles of the appropriate strength and filtration class in accordance with Table R63/A.1 and Table R63/E.1
• HOLD POINT: Placement of geotextile. Submit to the Client: Site sampling test results referred to in Clause 2.4 prior to placement of geotextile

name: Document Title: ITP-CIV-CAMMS-Type A Fill - Road (Supply and Install)
ITP Description: CAMMS-Type A Fill - Road (Supply and Install)
ITP approved for use by: Aldrin Guinchoma
Acceptance Criteria - Type A material shall comply with the requirements of Table 204.041 and shall be free of topsoil, deleterious and/or perishable matter.
Frequency - Once, for each material type
Verifying Documents - Supplier Material Conformance Certificate
Acceptance Criteria - Areas upon which fills are to be constructed shall be prepared for test rolling by the Contractor.
The Contractor shall not commence placing any fill on the prepared areas until the area has been reviewed by the Nominated Authority.
No fill shall be placed against or within 3 m of a structure until the foundation for the fill has been reviewed by the Nominated Authority
Frequency - Prior to commencement of fill works
Acceptance Criteria - Set out pegs in place and clearly mark out limits of works.
ATTACH: LOT MARKED UP LOCATION ON THE IFC DRAWING (LOT MAP)
Frequency - Each lot prior to commencement
Verifying Documents - Signed ITP, Lot Map
Acceptance Criteria - Type A material shall be spread and compacted in layers not exceeding a compacted thickness of 200 mm.
Acceptance Criteria - Each Layer shall be test rolled in accordance with Section 173. Where site access is restricted, verify with a pickaxe drop or similar, at the Nominated Authorities discretion.
Acceptance Criteria - Testing as per 204. Ensure testing is tracked and reports available.
• For work to be tested for compliance with Scale A or Scale B compaction requirements, the number of tests per test lot shall be six.
• For work to be tested for compliance with Scale C compaction requirements, the number of tests per test lot shall be three.
– Scale C: Mean Value of Density Ratio: 100%
• Lot size - the leser of one day's production or 5,000sqm
Frequency - Test the first 3 lots. Reduced min. frequency every 2nd lot of like material and work
Verifying Documents - Sign ITP, Attach Compaction Test Report

Acceptance Criteria - The top of the Type A material, Cut Floor Level and subgrade surfaces shall be prepared to level and shape within the tolerances specified in Clause 204.03 (g) to produce a smooth, hard, tightly bound surface, free from depressions capable of holding water).
Acceptance Criteria - Material Properties (Not Applicable for Scale C):
– Initial - 1 Lot Test to determine Assigned CBR and swell
– Reduced - 1 Single CBR test to confirm Assigned CBR and swell per every 2 lots
– Initial - 1 test for each lot tested for compaction
– Reduced - 1 test for every second lot tested for compaction
○ 1 Lot Test to determine: Assigned CBR and swell, Grading & Max. Particle Dimension, PI and PIx%Passing 0.425mm and permeability.
○ Where the first lot passes, no further testing required except where changes to the physical properties of the material are observed.
Verifying Documents - Sign ITP, Attach Material Property Test Report
Acceptance Criteria - The level at any point on the subgrade shall not lie more than 20 mm below a 3 m straightedge laid in any direction, except across a crown and water shall not pond at any point.
○ Where Scale C is nominated, random levelling is not required; however no point on the subgrade surface shall be more than 10 mm above or 30 mm below the specified level.
Verifying Documents - This ITP, Survey Conformance Report
Acceptance Criteria - Ensure that any NCRs pertaining to the lot / element / Work area that this ITP covers, have been closed in CAMs.
Frequency - Once, prior to closure of this lot / element / Work area
